cs.IT, cs.MM, cs.SI, cs.DS, cs.LG. 

The paper deals with information theory and compression, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The use of correlated side information sequences and the investigation of joint compression also suggest a possible fit with the cs.MM (Multimedia) and cs.SI (Signal Processing) sub-categories. The study of the rate-distortion function and the characterization of the associated trade-off between rate and distortion also suggest a possible fit with the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories.
